  "prompt": "What is the time complexity for reversing a string through recursion?",
  "response": "The time complexity for reversing a string through recursion is \\( O(n) \\), where \\( n \\) is the length of the string.\n\nHere's a brief explanation of how this works:\n\n1. **Recursive Calls**: In a recursive approach to reversing a string, you typically take the first character and append it to the result of reversing the rest of the string. For example, if the string is \"abc\", the process would look like this: \n\n   - Reverse(\"abc\") = \"a\" + Reverse(\"bc\")\n   - Reverse(\"bc\") = \"b\" + Reverse(\"c\")\n   - Reverse(\"c\") = \"c\" (base case)\n\n   After reaching the base case, the recursive calls begin to return and concatenate the characters in reverse order.\n\n2. **Number of Calls**: Each recursive call processes one character of the string, and there will be \\( n \\) calls for a string of length \\( n \\).\n\n3. **Work Done per Call**: For each recursive call, the operations performed (appending characters) take constant time, \\( O(1) \\).\n\nCombining these observations, we have \\( n \\) calls each taking \\( O(1) \\) time, leading to an overall time complexity of \\( O(n) \\).\n\nHowever, it's also worth noting that the auxiliary space complexity for this approach is \\( O(n) \\) due to the recursion stack, as each recursive call adds a new layer to the call stack until the base case is reached.",
